#!/usr/bin/env bash

cat <<'EOF'
{
  "hookSpecificOutput": {
    "hookEventName": "SessionStart",
    "additionalContext": "The Spwnr plugin is available, and its command surface now lives entirely under skills/. Use /using-spwnr as the main router: default to /spwnr-plan, then /spwnr-task, then implement. Use /spwnr-do for a bounded small task that does not need the full planning flow. `/spwnr-do` should use Skill, Read, Write, Edit, Agent, and spwnr resolve-workers, write a lightweight note under .claude/do/spwnr-do-<project-folder-name>-<YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS>-<slug>.md, keep direct worker selection to 1-3, redirect to /spwnr-worker-audit when coverage is weak, and redirect to /spwnr-plan when the task is broad, multi-stage, risky, or planning-sensitive. For non-trivial work, start with /spwnr-plan to align and lock the plan first. Planning should load spwnr-principle and spwnr-plan with Skill, ask only material clarification questions plus the execution review loop with AskUserQuestion, track blockers and review-loop outcomes with TodoWrite, inspect repo context with Read, persist the detailed plan to the latest active revision at .claude/plans/spwnr-<project-folder-name>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md or .claude/plans/spwnr-<project-folder-name>-<YYYY-MM-DD>-rN.md with Write or Edit, preview planning candidates with spwnr resolve-workers, and run a sequential planning expert loop with Agent for `research`, `draft`, and `review`. Planning should render execution-unit markers as one-line labels, preferably `- **unit_id**: unit-1`; compatible fallbacks like `- **unit_id:** unit-1` are tolerated, but do not bury `unit_id` in prose or tables. Minor revisions should update the same active revision, while a material re-plan should supersede the older revision and create the next revision file. Planning must choose `pipeline` or `team`, justify that choice, and persist the execution pattern. In `team` mode, prefer plans where parallel units do not edit the same file; keep shared-file execution only as an explicit exception with documented isolation or serialization. If planning-time registry lookup cannot cover those expert roles, stop with Worker Readiness Required, direct the user to /spwnr-worker-audit, and preserve the same active revision. After each successful plan write or revision, /spwnr-plan should ask whether to `Execute current plan`, `Continue improving plan`, or `End this round`; choosing `Execute current plan` should hand off into execution, `Continue improving plan` should revise the same active revision unless the request becomes a material re-plan, and `End this round` should stop cleanly. /spwnr-plan must not create tasks, teams, or worktrees from the planning loop, and any Agent use there must stay planning-only. /spwnr-task uses the same planning gate, requires the current run to receive `Execute current plan`, then reads the latest active revision with Read, appends the Approved Execution Spec with Edit, resolves registry candidates with spwnr resolve-workers, uses repeatable --unit briefs when multiple execution units need per-unit coverage, and routes to skills/spwnr-task/task-pipeline.md or skills/spwnr-task/task-team.md. The routed execution helper creates the queue with TaskCreate, validates it with TaskGet and TaskList, and keeps it current with TaskUpdate. Every execution task carries Plan, Unit, Mode, Worktree, Blocked, Owner, Files, Claim-Policy, Risk, and Plan-Approval metadata. `Blocked:` is reserved for current block state only, so new tasks should start with `Blocked: no` literally and keep sequencing in `Depends-On:` or task graph relations. High-risk tasks must reach Plan-Approval approved before completion. `pipeline` works without Claude team features. `team` may start multiple pipelines in parallel when the approved plan says so, and then uses TeamCreate, Agent, SendMessage, and TeamDelete. If team setup fails, stop with a worker-readiness recovery message instead of silently downgrading. If TaskCreate is blocked, do not execute anyway; repair the plan artifact or task metadata first. Superseded-plan tasks remain visible for audit, but only the latest active revision should drive execution or stop-hook blocking. Use /spwnr-worker-audit when registry health, installation, injection, or readiness recovery needs a deeper audit."
  }
}
EOF
